00:03:32.220 --> 00:03:38.039
And the first question we actually got during the live demo, and it came from Adam here

00:03:38.039 --> 00:03:43.880
asking, are there any performance benefits to using Shiny Core over Shiny Express?

00:03:44.320 --> 00:03:46.320
So Winston, I'll give you the floor.

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:47.559
Sure.

00:03:47.559 --> 00:03:51.600
So there's a couple of levels to this question.

00:03:51.600 --> 00:04:00.399
So in terms of the overhead for using Shiny Express or Shiny Core, there's a trivial amount

00:04:00.399 --> 00:04:06.440
like when it parses the code, where it has to evaluate each line and decide whether or

00:04:06.440 --> 00:04:13.759
not to use the return value of that and put that into the UI for the application.

00:04:14.639 --> 00:04:17.079
So that's really, really, really trivial.

00:04:17.079 --> 00:04:21.480
There is one thing that people should be aware of.

00:04:21.480 --> 00:04:29.239
I'm actually not completely sure if we have it detailed on the website at this point.

00:04:29.239 --> 00:04:39.480
But if you are developing locally, when you load a Shiny Express app, it runs the code

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:44.480
one time to generate the user interface components, and then it saves that.

00:04:44.480 --> 00:04:49.040
And then for each session that connects, so the first web browser that connects, it'll

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:55.799
run that code again to set up all the reactive stuff and the outputs.

00:04:55.799 --> 00:05:01.239
So and then for each, and that part is the same as for a Shiny Core app, and it runs

00:05:01.239 --> 00:05:02.600
the code.

00:05:02.600 --> 00:05:15.920
So it runs the code twice when you're developing locally for when you visit the app.

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:21.559
So that could be noticeable for local development for when you're deployed on a remote server.

00:05:21.559 --> 00:05:22.559
That shouldn't.

00:05:22.559 --> 00:05:26.880
Well, there are some cases where that could be noticeable.

00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:31.440
But we're working on ways to make it easier to sort of split up the code that needs to

00:05:31.440 --> 00:05:36.799
just run once for UI and the code that needs to run for the server.

00:05:36.799 --> 00:05:40.799
So we'll be writing more about that in depth in the future.

00:05:40.799 --> 00:05:41.799
Awesome.

00:05:41.799 --> 00:05:42.799
Thanks, Winston.

00:05:42.799 --> 00:05:45.899
All right, we're gonna move on to another question here.

00:05:45.899 --> 00:05:51.119
So is it possible to set up a standalone Shiny server that supports hosting both Python and

00:05:51.119 --> 00:05:53.239
our Shiny apps on the same instance?

00:05:53.239 --> 00:05:57.399
