00:06:00.000 --> 00:06:03.359
And then, Winston, you can feel free to add any additional comments there.

00:06:03.359 --> 00:06:09.519
So here at Posit, we do have a few solutions for taking your applications that are built

00:06:09.519 --> 00:06:13.640
in either R or Python and hosting them so you can easily share them with whoever.

00:06:13.640 --> 00:06:19.160
It could be your coworker, your boss, friends and family, whoever you want.

00:06:19.160 --> 00:06:24.399
So in terms of Shiny server, which is a tool some folks have probably heard of in the past,

00:06:24.399 --> 00:06:28.119
one of the first tools that we ever developed here at Posit allows you to take a Linux server

00:06:28.239 --> 00:06:31.299
and essentially convert it into like a hosting platform.

00:06:31.299 --> 00:06:35.600
And the open source version of Shiny server does allow you to have both Shiny applications

00:06:35.600 --> 00:06:37.640
built in R or Python.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:39.279
So it's a really great tool.

00:06:39.279 --> 00:06:43.679
Now, converting a Linux server into a kind of a hosting environment does require a little

00:06:43.679 --> 00:06:46.799
bit of IT and admin overhead.

00:06:46.799 --> 00:06:51.200
And you are just limited to Shiny application, that's pretty much about it.

00:06:51.200 --> 00:06:55.839
So we would certainly advocate for the use of one of our professional tools called Posit

00:06:55.839 --> 00:06:56.839
Connect.

00:06:56.839 --> 00:07:01.959
So Posit Connect is what we call our professional publishing platform because you can host multiple

00:07:01.959 --> 00:07:06.640
Shiny applications, both R, Python, you can host your Quarto documents, which we talked

00:07:06.640 --> 00:07:13.320
about in previous sessions, APIs and FastAPI, Flask apps, Bokeh, Streamlit, we have a ton

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:16.040
of different support for various content types.

00:07:16.040 --> 00:07:19.239
And again, they can all be hosted on the same server.

00:07:19.239 --> 00:07:24.200
And as the developer or the owner of the various content, you have a lot more control over

00:07:24.200 --> 00:07:26.279
it, say with Shiny server.

00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:30.440
You have control over who has access to it, how it runs on the server, so you can allocate

00:07:30.440 --> 00:07:32.480
more processes to it.

00:07:32.480 --> 00:07:35.480
You can really fine tune it to ensure a good user experience.

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:41.040
So that would be kind of my two cents in terms of hosting your Shiny applications.

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:43.519
Winston, do you have anything else you want to add there?

00:07:43.519 --> 00:07:45.119
No, that's great.

00:07:45.119 --> 00:07:46.119
Yeah.

00:07:46.119 --> 00:07:52.119
Well, actually, one other thing, you know, with Connect, every app that you deploy gets

00:07:52.119 --> 00:07:57.559
its own set of like, you know, Python version and Shiny version and all the packages.

00:07:57.559 --> 00:07:59.519
That's true for R and Python.

00:07:59.519 --> 00:08:04.600
Whereas with Shiny server, it's, you know, all the apps, they're deployed under just

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:07.880
like one user and they don't have that sort of isolation.

00:08:07.880 --> 00:08:12.839
So it's harder to manage, you know, versions and dependencies and stuff.

00:08:12.839 --> 00:08:18.519
So if that's important to you, Connect is a better tool for that.

00:08:18.519 --> 00:08:19.519
Excellent.

