00:11:19.119 --> 00:11:22.960
All right, so moving on to the next question here in the chat.

00:11:22.960 --> 00:11:28.520
So you mentioned that there are limitations on saving data when using the web app.

00:11:28.520 --> 00:11:33.359
How about when using a server-based app like SQL Alchemy?

00:11:33.359 --> 00:11:40.119
Okay, I think this is referring to Shiny Live.

00:11:40.119 --> 00:11:50.280
So, Shiny Live is a way of running Shiny where Python is not running on the server.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:54.000
There's a special version of Python that's compiled to WebAssembly, which runs in your

00:11:54.000 --> 00:11:55.200
browser.

00:11:55.200 --> 00:12:02.840
So when you deploy an application that way, there are some benefits to it.

00:12:02.840 --> 00:12:06.760
But there are also some limitations to it, like you can't...

00:12:06.760 --> 00:12:09.320
There's no server that it's running on.

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:11.679
The server is just a dumb web server, and it sends you these...

00:12:11.679 --> 00:12:16.979
It's like a static website, essentially, and all the Python code runs in your browser.

00:12:16.979 --> 00:12:22.239
So there's nowhere to save data to.

00:12:22.280 --> 00:12:28.159
Now, for a traditional Shiny deployment, I think that's what's meant here by a server-based

00:12:28.159 --> 00:12:30.159
app.

00:12:30.159 --> 00:12:31.159
You can do anything.

00:12:31.159 --> 00:12:36.719
So if you're running Python code on the server, and so if you want to, if you've got a SQL

00:12:36.719 --> 00:12:43.679
database or if you want to just write files to disk as a CSV or whatever format, you can

00:12:43.679 --> 00:12:44.679
do that.

00:12:44.679 --> 00:12:46.239
It's just running Python code.

00:12:46.239 --> 00:12:52.479
So that's a big difference between Shiny live and regular Shiny deployment.

00:12:52.479 --> 00:12:53.479
Awesome.

00:12:53.479 --> 00:12:54.479
Yeah.

