All right, so I'm going to do move on to another question here, which I really like this question.

00:14:34.799 --> 00:14:36.880
I think Winston can talk a lot about it.

00:14:36.880 --> 00:14:41.840
So the question is, you seem to be doing a lot with Python.

00:14:41.840 --> 00:14:44.440
What is happening with R development in Shiny?

00:14:44.440 --> 00:14:48.799
All right, that is really, that's a great question.

00:14:48.799 --> 00:14:57.679
So it's true, we are doing a lot with Python and Shiny for Python.

00:14:57.679 --> 00:15:05.219
And more of our energy is focused there than on Shiny for R. And there's a bunch of reasons

00:15:05.219 --> 00:15:06.219
for this.

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:13.020
One of them is that Shiny for R has been around for close to 12 years now.

00:15:13.020 --> 00:15:17.580
And Shiny for Python has not been around for two years, hasn't been around for two years.

00:15:17.580 --> 00:15:25.500
So for R, Shiny is pretty mature, pretty well established.

00:15:25.500 --> 00:15:35.419
There's not a whole lot right now that we're doing the Shiny for R, except for there's

00:15:35.780 --> 00:15:36.780
various UI stuff.

00:15:36.780 --> 00:15:41.940
So there's like a lot of the UI stuff, like in BSLib, like for sidebar styling and cards

00:15:41.940 --> 00:15:46.299
and all that sort of stuff, that is actually happening in R first.

00:15:46.299 --> 00:15:51.419
And then we bring that code over to Python, because a lot of that is, the reason we can

00:15:51.419 --> 00:15:56.380
bring that code over is because a lot of it's JavaScript and CSS stuff.

00:15:56.380 --> 00:16:00.739
And then we port the R code to Python code.

00:16:00.739 --> 00:16:04.820
Now there's actually, there's stuff that happens in the other direction as well, where

00:16:04.820 --> 00:16:13.580
we have been implementing stuff in Python and we have ideas that sort of feel natural

00:16:13.580 --> 00:16:16.539
or that come up from Python that then we brought over to R.

00:16:16.539 --> 00:16:22.659
So a recent example of that is being able to run asynchronous extended tasks.

00:16:22.659 --> 00:16:26.739
So to be able to launch something in the background in a Shiny app, and then keep using your Shiny

00:16:26.739 --> 00:16:30.659
app while some computation happens in the background.

00:16:30.659 --> 00:16:34.260
That's something that Joe Chang implemented.

00:16:34.260 --> 00:16:38.419
And we did that first in Python and we brought it over to R as well.

00:16:38.419 --> 00:16:41.979
So there is sort of this exchange that's still going back and forth.

00:16:41.979 --> 00:16:50.140
But again, Shiny for R is a lot more mature and Shiny for Python, there's still a lot

00:16:50.140 --> 00:16:57.020
of stuff that we need to do to get, even to get like feature parity for Shiny for R.

00:16:57.140 --> 00:17:01.219
Yeah, and that's Shiny, actually, I should mention, so Shiny Express, that's another

00:17:01.219 --> 00:17:08.900
thing that we were able to do in Python and sort of looked around and we saw, oh, okay,

00:17:08.900 --> 00:17:10.780
it's possible to do things this way here.

00:17:10.780 --> 00:17:11.780
Let's try that.

00:17:11.780 --> 00:17:19.260
And then, so, and we may, I'm not sure, well, it depends on what people ask for, but like

00:17:19.260 --> 00:17:25.500
I have a sketch, I have a basic version of that working for R as well, but in order to

00:17:25.500 --> 00:17:30.260
get that fully baked, there's a lot of work in terms of documentation and a lot of details

00:17:30.260 --> 00:17:31.260
that need to be done.

00:17:31.260 --> 00:17:34.619
But we might, we could bring that over to R as well.

00:17:34.619 --> 00:17:39.060
So there is an exchange of things that are going in both directions.

00:17:39.060 --> 00:17:40.060
Gotcha.

00:17:40.060 --> 00:17:41.060
Thanks.

