00:17:48.459 --> 00:18:00.900
We, our team, we merged a PR pull request yesterday to add a dark mode widget to Shiny.

00:18:00.900 --> 00:18:05.979
So it's actually, well, gosh, I don't know if I can show you here, but it's really cool.

00:18:05.979 --> 00:18:08.500
You click on it and there's this really cool animation where it's like, there's like a

00:18:08.500 --> 00:18:13.819
sun thing and it just turns into like a moon.

00:18:13.819 --> 00:18:16.540
So yes, that is there.

00:18:16.540 --> 00:18:18.819
That's in the development version of Shiny.

00:18:18.819 --> 00:18:26.180
Oh, and I think it's already in Shiny for R or BSLib on the R side.

00:18:26.180 --> 00:18:27.180
Yeah.

00:18:27.180 --> 00:18:28.180
Yeah.

00:18:28.180 --> 00:18:29.180
I believe it's in BSLib.

00:18:29.180 --> 00:18:30.180
Yeah.

00:18:30.180 --> 00:18:32.859
So yeah, stay tuned for that.

00:18:32.859 --> 00:18:34.060
All right.

00:18:34.060 --> 00:18:38.380
So this is a really good question that I know I've gotten from the data science community

00:18:38.380 --> 00:18:39.619
a lot.

00:18:39.619 --> 00:18:43.739
Can you compare and contrast Shiny Express and Streamlit?

00:18:44.660 --> 00:18:47.619
So I'm not sure if maybe this would be, you can boil it down to just like Shiny versus

00:18:47.619 --> 00:18:48.619
Streamlit really.

00:18:48.619 --> 00:18:49.619
Yeah.

00:18:49.619 --> 00:18:50.619
All right.

00:18:50.619 --> 00:18:56.140
This is, this is always a big question.

00:18:56.140 --> 00:19:03.660
So you know, one of the things that Shiny does really well, I think in comparison to

00:19:03.660 --> 00:19:09.020
Streamlit is the execution model can let you do a lot more stuff.

00:19:09.020 --> 00:19:15.420
So like when you change, when you change an input on a Shiny application, you know,

00:19:15.420 --> 00:19:19.500
that sends a message to the server and the server knows like, Hey, I just, I need to

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:22.900
recompute everything that uses this input value and nothing else.

00:19:22.900 --> 00:19:27.020
And then, you know, it does a computation and it sends the updated outputs back to the

00:19:27.020 --> 00:19:28.020
web browser.

00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:32.500
And that's, that can be quite efficient.

00:19:32.500 --> 00:19:37.300
And contrast that with the, you know, the Streamlit model where you do anything, you

00:19:37.300 --> 00:19:40.699
change any inputs and it reruns the whole script over and over again.

00:19:40.699 --> 00:19:47.160
And then they have, you know, they have tools to try to try to reduce the amount of computation

00:19:47.160 --> 00:19:51.540
and data that's sent over to the, to the browser, like caching.

00:19:51.540 --> 00:19:56.140
But that's sort of like, that stuff is sort of a, it's sort of an add on.

00:19:56.140 --> 00:19:59.140
And it's like, it makes things more complicated, whereas that's just sort of the basic part

00:19:59.140 --> 00:20:00.140
of Shiny.

00:20:00.140 --> 00:20:09.020
But for Shiny core, there's more code you have to write compared to a Streamlit app.

00:20:09.020 --> 00:20:13.219
So, and so that, you know, that I think was a hurdle for people to get over.

00:20:13.219 --> 00:20:17.619
So, so, you know, we're hoping that, Hey, with Shiny express, there's, there's so there's,

00:20:17.619 --> 00:20:20.420
we've removed a lot of the boilerplate code.

00:20:20.420 --> 00:20:23.300
You can, you can keep things a lot more concise.

00:20:23.300 --> 00:20:27.819
And so hopefully, you know, hopefully that'll resonate with people and they'll be like,

00:20:27.819 --> 00:20:31.619
okay, I'm just, just going to just go ahead and just get started writing this app with

00:20:31.619 --> 00:20:33.699
just this minimal amount of code.

00:20:33.699 --> 00:20:42.339
And and yeah, and so hopefully that will be, you know, people will get started really quickly

00:20:42.339 --> 00:20:43.339
with it.

00:20:43.339 --> 00:20:44.339
All right.

00:20:44.339 --> 00:20:50.140
So we've got another question here.

00:20:50.140 --> 00:20:55.579
How to modularize the Shiny express app like the traditional Shiny core?

00:20:55.579 --> 00:20:56.579
Okay.

00:20:57.020 --> 00:21:00.099
Another great question for Shiny.

00:21:00.099 --> 00:21:05.339
So for those that aren't familiar with this, there's a thing that we have in Shiny called

00:21:05.339 --> 00:21:07.180
Shiny modules.

00:21:07.180 --> 00:21:11.239
This was originally an R and it's not.

00:21:11.239 --> 00:21:14.420
So in the Python world, there's already, you know, modules already mean something else

00:21:14.420 --> 00:21:18.260
in Python, but we're talking about Shiny modules.

00:21:18.260 --> 00:21:22.699
We specifically mean like components, Shiny components that you can use on a page and

00:21:22.699 --> 00:21:27.339
reuse and they're sort of encapsulated.

00:21:27.339 --> 00:21:35.579
So in a Shiny express app, you can use module, you can use modules that are written with

00:21:35.579 --> 00:21:38.800
the Shiny core syntax.

00:21:38.800 --> 00:21:41.420
You can already do that.

00:21:41.420 --> 00:21:46.859
Now if you want to be able to write a module using the Shiny express syntax, that's something

00:21:46.859 --> 00:21:48.739
that we're working on right now.

00:21:48.739 --> 00:21:54.099
And yeah, that, you know, that's, there's some details about that that make it a little

00:21:54.099 --> 00:21:55.099
bit challenging.

00:21:55.099 --> 00:22:01.180
Like how should, you know, how do we want people to be able to write this code and,

00:22:01.180 --> 00:22:04.420
you know, express what they want to do.

00:22:04.420 --> 00:22:07.219
But we're going to do it.

00:22:07.219 --> 00:22:09.780
So yeah, we'll get there.

00:22:09.780 --> 00:22:11.300
And sorry if there's yelling in the background.

00:22:11.300 --> 00:22:12.859
My kids are homesick today.

00:22:12.859 --> 00:22:16.939
So there's a little bit of chaos.

00:22:17.739 --> 00:22:18.739
All good.

00:22:18.739 --> 00:22:19.739
We can barely hear it.

