00:22:27.979 --> 00:22:33.699
But in the meantime, we got one more question about kind of your development of Shiny applications.

00:22:33.699 --> 00:22:38.260
And this question is asking if there are any advantages to using Visual Studio Code instead

00:22:38.260 --> 00:22:41.819
of the RStudio IDE for developing Shiny applications?

00:22:42.819 --> 00:22:48.180
Yeah, I would say, you know, for the, if you're developing Shiny for R applications, the RStudio

00:22:48.180 --> 00:22:50.579
IDE is definitely the way to go.

00:22:50.579 --> 00:22:54.780
It's there's, there's a lot, there's a lot of stuff, a lot of work that's gone into that

00:22:54.780 --> 00:23:02.180
to make it, to improve the experience of writing Shiny applications for R.

00:23:02.180 --> 00:23:10.140
If you're writing Shiny for Python applications, I think, you know, it's, I would, well, and

00:23:10.140 --> 00:23:17.339
I do use the VS, I do use VS Code instead of RStudio IDE because, because it's really,

00:23:17.339 --> 00:23:18.939
it's really good for Python stuff.

00:23:18.939 --> 00:23:26.020
So, and, and there's, you know, this extension, this Shiny, the Shiny for Python extension

00:23:26.020 --> 00:23:27.020
for VS Code.

00:23:27.020 --> 00:23:32.140
And it, and it understands, you know, like Python syntax highlighting and type checking

00:23:32.140 --> 00:23:35.180
and all sorts of stuff that, that can be really useful.

00:23:35.180 --> 00:23:39.380
Whereas, whereas I know RStudio does, the RStudio IDE does some of those things, but

00:23:39.380 --> 00:23:45.939
it's not, it's, there hasn't been as much effort put into that on the RStudio IDE side.

00:23:45.939 --> 00:23:46.939
Gotcha.

00:23:46.939 --> 00:23:47.939
Yeah.

00:23:47.939 --> 00:23:54.140
And I can also just kind of one plug for one of our other professional tools, Posit Workbench.

00:23:54.140 --> 00:23:59.859
One of the IDEs within Posit Workbench is Visual Studio Code, and we've actually incorporated

00:23:59.859 --> 00:24:05.380
a Posit Workbench extension, which allows you to run applications, interactive applications

00:24:05.380 --> 00:24:09.180
as like a proxied server from within your development environment.

00:24:09.979 --> 00:24:13.859
So it's a great way to develop Shiny applications within VS Code and then run them kind of within

00:24:13.859 --> 00:24:17.420
your development environment, see those changes kind of live as you're developing.

00:24:17.420 --> 00:24:18.979
So a really cool feature.

00:24:18.979 --> 00:24:24.739
All right, we've got another question here, maybe a quick answer, but would it be possible

00:24:24.739 --> 00:24:29.699
to call a Shiny app or to call a Shiny app from Jupyter Notebook?

00:24:29.699 --> 00:24:32.660
If not, is there an integration planned?

00:24:33.660 --> 00:24:36.660
It is definitely possible.

00:24:36.660 --> 00:24:40.500
Sorry, I'm thinking back.

00:24:40.500 --> 00:24:47.219
I had at some point in the past, I had made it possible to launch a Shiny app from a Jupyter

00:24:47.219 --> 00:24:48.219
Notebook.

00:24:48.219 --> 00:24:49.219
It was a little bit hacky.

00:24:49.219 --> 00:24:53.099
You know, there's actually, I think there's a couple of different ways somebody might

00:24:53.099 --> 00:24:54.099
want to go about it.

00:24:54.099 --> 00:24:55.780
So one of them is like, hey, I'm in a Jupyter Notebook.

00:24:55.780 --> 00:24:59.020
I want to launch this Shiny app.

00:24:59.020 --> 00:25:02.140
And they could write the code in the Jupyter Notebook and then launch it.

00:25:02.140 --> 00:25:08.099
That is, sorry, launch it and then view that from a different web browser window.

00:25:08.099 --> 00:25:09.099
That is possible.

00:25:09.099 --> 00:25:12.660
It's like I said, that part is a little hacky.

00:25:12.660 --> 00:25:23.780
There was actually something where Joe Chang, he had created, he actually had some Jupyter

00:25:23.780 --> 00:25:24.780
integration for Shiny.

00:25:24.780 --> 00:25:28.500
So you could write code that was sort of like Shiny Express.

00:25:28.540 --> 00:25:33.900
And then the stuff would just show up in the Jupyter Notebook, like the inputs and outputs.

00:25:33.900 --> 00:25:39.219
So we actually, you know, I don't know, there's maybe like a month or so of work that was

00:25:39.219 --> 00:25:43.180
put into that.

00:25:43.180 --> 00:25:48.739
And it's not clear, well, we weren't sure where to go with that.

00:25:48.739 --> 00:25:52.180
Like if that's really where we're going to keep putting more effort.

00:25:52.180 --> 00:25:58.739
So we ended up focusing on Shiny Express instead of continuing on that Jupyter path.

00:25:58.739 --> 00:26:04.859
But you know, I mean, if that sounds like something that a lot of people would be interested

00:26:04.859 --> 00:26:08.219
in, then we might re-revisit that decision.

00:26:08.219 --> 00:26:11.859
Because I mean, it was actually kind of cool to be able to just like put in the stuff,

00:26:11.859 --> 00:26:17.260
you know, like inputs and outputs in the Jupyter Notebook and just be able to have that show

00:26:17.260 --> 00:26:18.459
up.

